<p><a name="Notes" id="Notes"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Differential_geometry&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Notes">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Notes</span></h2>
<ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-0"><b><a href="#cite_ref-0" title="">^</a></b> It is easy to show that the area preserving condition (or the twisting condition) cannot be removed. Note that if one tries to extend such a theorem to higher dimensions, one would probably guess that a volume preserving map of a certain type must have fixed points. This is false in dimensions greater than 3.</li>
<li id="cite_note-1"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1" title="">^</a></b> Paul Marriott and Mark Salmon, "Applications of Differential Geometry to Econometrics".</li>
<li id="cite_note-2"><b><a href="#cite_ref-2" title="">^</a></b> Jonathan H. Manton, "On the role of differential geometry in signal processing" <a href="http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/iel5/9711/30654/01416480.pdf?arnumber=1416480" class="external autonumber" title="http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/iel5/9711/30654/01416480.pdf?arnumber=1416480" rel="nofollow">[1]</a>.</li>
</ol>
